        </score>
      </mdiv>
    </body>
  </music>
</mei>

<!--
VOICING PLAN — Over Kidron Jesus Treadeth (G major)
=====================================================
This hymn lives modally in E minor (relative minor of G major). The melody
frequently touches Eb (chromatic lowered 7th in Em context), and the chord
annotations include many non-diatonic chromatic chords. Strategy: use diatonic
G-major substitutions (VIm for Em, VII° for F#°, IIm for Am, IV for C).

PHRASE 1 (mm. 1-4): VIm-VII°-VIm-IV pattern establishes minor feel
- m1: LH "334" on VIm (E B G), open quinta; RH mirrors with close 3rds
- m2: Chromatic melody Eb4 kept in melody staff only; harp stays diatonic
  Substitution: Eb+ → V (D) as safest diatonic stand-in
- m3: IVΔ in LH (C G C E B) — four-note close position; richest bar so far
- m4: I–V–I cadence; LH four notes on I (G D G B)

PHRASE 2 (mm. 5-8): Higher register, fuller chords
- m5: Same harmonic shape but RH moves to high register (B4–F#5)
- m6: IIm–VII°–V–III; III (B major) used to accommodate "A" annotation
- m7: IVΔ7 in LH (C G E B) — richest chord of this phrase; VII°7 passing
- m8: I full at cadence: 4-note RH (G B D), 4-note LH (G D G B)

PHRASE 3 (mm. 9-12): Climbing sequence toward climax
- m9: V7 in LH adds seventh for color (D F# A C); VIm gives contrast
- m10: VII°–I–V; V gets 4-note LH with added octave (D A F# D)
- m11: IIIø7 in second beat adds half-diminished color
- m12: Descent VII°–IIm–VIm; final VIm has 4-note LH

PHRASE 4 (mm. 13-18): Final build and minor cadence
- m13: IIm–IV alternation; LH grows to 4 notes on IIm (A E A C)
- m14: VIm–VII°–VIm–IIm; four-note LH on VIm (E B G E)
- m15: Complex chromatic passage; substitutions keep harp diatonic
- m16: IIm–VII° sustained halves; both have 4-note LH
- m17: VII° whole note — penultimate tension (4-note LH)
- m18: Final VIm whole — minor ending; LH five notes (E B E G B) — maximum sonority

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS
========================
- Inner LH voice consistently follows scale steps: G–E–F#–E–G across phrases 1-2
- RH alto line: G4→F#4→E4→D4 descending third in mm. 1-4 mirrors bass descent
- m17→m18: VII°→VIm (F# A C → E G B) — each voice moves by half or whole step
  F#→E, A→G, C→B — smooth three-voice contrary resolution

TEXTURE ARC
===========
- mm. 1-4:  Sparse VIm center. 2 RH, 3 LH. Minor modal feel.
- mm. 5-8:  Moderate. RH reaches upper register. 3 RH on I/V.
- mm. 9-12: Full. V7 and IVΔ7 for color. 4 LH throughout.
- mm. 13-18: Maximum. 4 RH + 4-5 LH. Final minor chord full sonority.
-->
